<div class="about-education">
	<h4 class="about-q">What did you study in school?</h4>
	<p class="about-answer">I earned my B.A. in Women's Studies from the University of California, Riverside in 2009. I followed that up with a M.A. in Women's Studies in 2011 from San Diego State University. Though I'd initially planned to pursue a doctorate in sociology, I realized that my passion and interests no longer lied in academia, but in programming. In 2014, I began my career transition by earning a certificate in Ruby Programming from the University of Washington in August.</p>
</div>

<div class="about-care">
	<h4 class="about-q">What you care about?</h4>
	<p class="about-answer">As my B.A. and M.A. majors might suggest, I care deeply about social justice issues, particularly as they relate to gender, race, and sexuality. I still use and share this knowledge on a daily basis to promote awareness for women and minority issues within the tech world, whether it relates to the STEM pipeline, retention, or designing apps for more diverse audiences.</p>
	<p class="about-answer">Although I don't teach for a living, my previous experiences teaching undergraduate university courses have given me a deep appreciation for education, teaching, and pedagogy. I hope to use my teaching and public speaking skills to present talks at tech conferences in the near future.</p>
</div>

<div class="about-skills">
	<h4 class="about-q">What other non-technical skills do you have?</h4>
	<p class="about-answer">Because of my round-about journey to becoming a developer, I've been fortunate enough to pick up a number of non-technical skills that make me a better employee and colleague. </p>
	<p class="about-answer">From 2011 to 2014, I worked as a college textbook editor and managed the production of more than 60 books per semester, a job that required me to stay organized, communicative, have a sharp eye for errors and typos (which still comes in quite handy while debugging and proofreading code). This project management role taught me how to balance the big picture while staying attentive to the details, and also honed my ability to work closely with clients in order to serve niche audiences. During that time, I was also responsible for training and hiring new teammates, which allowed me to put my experiences as teacher and mentor to good use.</p>
	<p class="about-answer">I'm also autodidactic, which means that I feel constantly driven to teach myself new things. To that end, I've gained a wide range of software experience, including the Adobe Creative Suite (particularly InDesign and Illustrator), music creation software (Logic Pro and Garageband), and your classic office stand-bys like Microsoft Office and Apple's iWork suite.</p>

</div>

